":"1272","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","1315":"1315","1225":"1225","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1365":"1365","1276":"1276","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","Rostock, Rostock, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Deutschland":"Rostock, Rostock, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Germany","Rostock, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Germany":"Rostock, Rostock, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baumgarten","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Hans, Horst, Klaus, Otto, Ewald, Lothar, Wilhelm.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name or metonymic occupational name for someone who owned or lived by an orchard or was employed in one, from Middle High German <i>boumgarte</i> ‘orchard’ (a compound of <i>boum</i> ‘tree’ + <i>garte</i> ‘enclosure’), German <i>Baumgarten</i>. There are also several villages named with this word, and so in some cases the surname may have originated as a habitational name from one of these. As a Jewish name, it is mainly artificial."],"variants":[{"name":"Bangert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Hans, Horst, Klaus, Otto, Ewald, Lothar, Wilhelm.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name or metonymic occupational name for someone who owned or lived by an orchard or was employed in one, from Middle High German <i>boumgarte</i> ‘orchard’ (a compound of <i>boum</i> ‘tree’ + <i>garte</i> ‘enclosure’), German <i>Baumgarten</i>. There are also several villages named with this word, and so in some cases the surname may have originated as a habitational name from one of these. As a Jewish name, it is mainly artificial."]},{"name":"Baumgard","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Baumgarten  ."]},{"name":"Baumgart","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Helmut, Kurt, Hans, Alfons, Dietrich, Eldor, Erwin, Fritz, Gerhard, Guenther, Hanns.","German and Jewish: variant of   Baumgarten  ."]},{"name":"Baumgartel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Kurt.","South German (<b>Baumgärtel</b>): from a diminutive of   Baumgarten  ."]},{"name":"Baumgardt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Horst.","German: variant of   Baumgarten  ."]},{"name":"Baumgartner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Fritz, Hans, Helmut, Alois, Otto, Erwin, Johann, Meggan, Dietmar, Ernst, Franz.","German and Swiss German (also <b>Baumgärtner</b>):","occupational name for someone who owned or worked in an orchard, from an agent derivative of   Baumgarten  ."]},{"name":"Bongard","meanings":["German: from Middle Low German <i>bōm</i> ‘tree’ + <i>gard</i> ‘garden’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived by an orchard or a nickname for someone who owned or worked in one. Compare   Baumgarten  .","Dutch: variant of   Bogard   or   Bogaard  , cognates of 1.","French: habitational name from a minor locality named with <i>bon</i> ‘good’ + <i>gard</i>, the objective case of Old French <i>gardin</i> ‘garden’."]}]},{"name":"N.N.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When N.N. Baumgarten was born in 1280, her father, Engelbert Baumgarten, was 56 and her mother, Adelheid N., was 31. She had at least 1 son with Hermann Lise or Lyse. She died in 1305, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1280–1305":"1280–1305","1270–1300":"1270–1300","1272–1350":"1272–1350","1274–1315":"1274–1315","1276–1345":"1276–1345","1260–1308":"1260–1308","1304–1365":"1304–1365","1225–1283":"1225–1283","1250–1317":"1250–1317","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","13